  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17:7-13 Micah thought it was a sign of God's favour to him and his images, that a Levite should come to his door. Thus those who please themselves with their own delusions, if Providence unexpectedly bring any thing to their hands that further them in their evil way, are apt from thence to think that God is pleased with them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Baal-tamar is only mentioned here. It took its name from some palm-tree that grew there; perhaps the same as the \"palm-tree of Deborah, between Ramah and Bethel\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the exact locality here indicated, since \"the highway\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " along which the Israelites enticed the Benjamites to pursue them, leads straight to Ramah, which lay only a mile beyond the point where the two ways branch off.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The meadows of Gibeah - The word rendered \"meadow\" is only found here. According to its etymology, it ought to mean a \"bare open place\", which is particularly unsuitable for an ambush. However, by a change in the vowel-points, without any alteration in the letters, it becomes the common word for \"a cavern\". ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The meadows of Gibeah - The word rendered \"meadow\" is only found here. According to its etymology, it ought to mean a \"bare open place\", which is particularly unsuitable for an ambush. However, by a change in the vowel-points, without any alteration in the letters, it becomes the common word for \"a cavern\". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
